{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff (classifier -> API client payload), not model judgment. A local integration test with a stub transport can capture the outbound request and assert all taxonomy labels are present. Rejected higher levels: behavior text is about request content (`includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels`), which disqualifies Agentic/Workflow because no assertion depends on model output quality or multi-step agent decisions; real network/OS is not required, so System is not required.","test_description":"Wire classifier with a fake API client that records outbound payload. Call classify with a known taxonomy and assert the sent prompt/fields contain every label exactly once before dispatch.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is best caught at response handoff (API response parsing + normalization + return value). A stubbed API response with an out-of-taxonomy label exercises the real module wiring and catches forwarding bugs. Rejected Agentic/System: behavior text is explicit mapping logic (`returns \"unknown\"`) and does not require real model quality or real network effects.","test_description":"Use classifier + stub API client. Stub response label `medical` while taxonomy is `legal, technical, financial, other`; assert returned label is `unknown` and raw `medical` is never exposed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior is deterministic normalization logic on identical input; no module boundary, I/O, or model decision is required. Rejected higher levels: text scopes to `normalization step` and `identical raw API responses`, which disqualifies System/Agentic/Workflow.","test_description":"Call normalization function repeatedly with the same raw payload variants (case/whitespace fixtures) and assert stable identical final label each run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Requires real AI API behavior across repeated calls; stubs would mask non-deterministic model/provider variation. Behavior explicitly says `repeated live API calls`, so correctness depends on real model outputs in production conditions. Rejected Workflow: only repeated single-step classification calls, not a multi-agent pipeline.","test_description":"Run N real classification calls for identical input against the live provider, log provider raw outputs and normalized labels, and assert label stability whenever provider response text is unchanged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure appears at boundary between budgeting logic and dispatch decision (truncate/reject vs send). A stubbed client can verify whether dispatch occurred and with what payload length. Rejected System/Agentic: behavior is pre-dispatch policy enforcement (`before dispatch`), not live network behavior or model-output quality.","test_description":"Configure a small token budget, send oversized document, and assert policy outcome (truncate or reject) plus dispatch behavior via fake client (sent truncated payload or no call made).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.45,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Validation depends on real AI API call metadata (`provider-reported token usage`). Mocked usage would always follow fixture values and can hide real tokenizer/model behavior drift. Rejected Integration: behavior is not only plumbing; it asserts real provider accounting stays within budget.","test_description":"Execute real calls for representative documents, capture provider usage fields (prompt/completion/total tokens), and assert total tokens <= configured budget for each call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary failure boundary is retry orchestration (rate-limit signal -> backoff -> retry -> success) across local modules. A deterministic stub can reproduce 429/Retry-After and verify wait/retry behavior without real network. Rejected System: behavior does not require OS/network primitives beyond controllable HTTP semantics; rejected Agentic/Workflow because no model-output correctness or multi-agent sequence is asserted.","test_description":"Stub API to return rate-limit error first, then success. Use controllable clock/sleeper to assert module waits per policy and retries, finally returning success instead of propagating initial error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.23,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
